It is easy to give up if you only compare yourself to other artists, everyone is at different portions of the journey and your journey with art may look vastly different. You have to also realize how long it really takes to get good with focused practice, then consider how much focused, guided practice you actually do.

The main thing that gets in the way of new artists is thinking that (1) you will get better quickly, (2) perfectionism, (3) putting yourself down for not meeting expectations,(4) not practicing and studying with focus, and (5) being unable to accept failing again and again and again and again.

I believe in you, anon. Don't give up, just keep drawing and learning.

Well, there's the overarching conflict you have that ties chapters together. Those are your more general beats.
But with what I write, having a shift in each scene or conversation is paramount.
I'll use an example from a future piece with all the details scrubbed so there are no spoilers
I can define the chapter in three sentences, that's it
But in each of those (which reflect about a third of the chapter), there's another layer of conflict-response-resolution.

Where I want the reader's attention goes like this
>OK, so we're getting a really brief recap and run into an immediate problem
that's the first conflict-response-resolution, which serves as a conflict one step up
>And who are these people?
>OH FUCKING CRAP
>YOU GOTTA GET SOME ANSWERS
>YEAH, FUCK 'EM UP!
and the second, which is the response to the previous c-r-r
>alright, it's answer time
>YOU FUCKING BASTARD WRITEFAG
>well, that's an even bigger answer
>we are in even deeper shit than we thought
and the third, which caps but also hooks the reader to go on and think about anything I didn't wrap up; maybe those are chekov's guns or clues or foreshadowing for much later

during the World Wars you had the rise of chemical munitions, mass-manufactured guns, airplanes, trench warfare...
>lack of modern telecommunications infrastructure...
If you're looking at the immediate post-WWII state, then all it is was taking stuff that got prototyped in WWII. Radio tech was the internet of its day, and the more advanced tech once we had practical computing was like the difference between a Hercules graphics card and the original Voodoo
And you have to go even further back. Crypto from the Middle ages to the Cold War was all about how fast you could transmit and how hard it was to decrypt if intercepted.
>espionage at an all time high, with nuclear stakes

>pace of technological progress so rapid, that anything seems possible...
At any period of tech explosion, the same is true.
One day, we'll be considered quaint for our 64bit procs that were supposedly a major leap over the early 8bit stuff and that over ancient discrete computing tech

>>46544423
My general point was that we stand on the shoulders of the past
People concentrate on tech expansions, but we rarely talk about the contractions. In early airplanes, you felt things; now many aircraft are inherently unstable and need computers. Early discrete computers, you programmed down to the bare metal if necessary; these days there are so many layers between you and the registers that the programing language (or more properly, the libraries) are the tool instead of the CPU. Math? A certain kind of intelligence died out after the shift from analog computing. People used to understand it differently because they got their hands working.

The Cold War stuff is easy now because there's still living people that knew the stuff and the basics of some of the tech still is easily explainable if you know our level.
I have this sneaking suspicion that non-electrical analog tech like letterlocking will make a comeback as an adjunct to an increasingly cyberspace-oriented world. You can't hack what isn't online. You can subvert the person, however.

I see patterns. History is fucking crazy and I love characters that are living in the wrong time but know how to work through the available tools to do things no one else can
